<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,800,760,787]" box="[189,800,760,787]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,800,760,787]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,800,760,787]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Ecology, distribution and associated diatom flora</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,1399,808,1333]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<taxonomicName box="[189,507,808,834]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Achnanthidiaceae" genus="Achnanthidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Achnanthales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="sieminskae">
<emphasis box="[189,507,808,834]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Achnanthidium sieminskae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described as a brackish-littoral taxon from a tidal flat near the Kerguelen Islands (
<bibRefCitation author="Witkowski A. &amp; Kulikovskiy M. &amp; Riaux-Gobin C." box="[458,719,843,869]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="61 - 68" refId="ref10775" refString="Witkowski A., Kulikovskiy M. &amp; Riaux-Gobin C. 2012. Achnanthidium sieminskae, a new diatom species from the Kerguelen Archipelago (Austral Islands). In: Wolowski K., Kaczmarska I., Ehreman J. M. &amp; Wojtal A. Z. (eds) Current advances in algal taxonomy and its applications: phylogenetic, ecological and applied perspective: 61 - 68. Polish Academy of Sciences, Krakow." type="book chapter" year="2012">
Witkowski 
<emphasis box="[594,652,843,869]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
) but the authors already expressed some doubts about this observation. Most likely, their population was the result of a riverine deposition in the marine Bossière fjord on Kerguelen. As they stated themselves, the only way to find out would be the analysis of the living material which was unfortunately no longer available at the time of their publication. We reported this taxon (as 
<taxonomicName box="[356,553,986,1012]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Achnanthidiaceae" genus="Achnanthidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Achnanthales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="minutissimum">
<emphasis box="[356,553,986,1012]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">A. minutissimum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) from a large number of purely freshwater habitats ranging from small pools to larger lakes and even streams from all sub-Antarctic islands in both the Indian and Atlantic Ocean (
<bibRefCitation author="Van de Vijver B. &amp; Beyens L." box="[281,649,1057,1084]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="359 - 368" refId="ref10102" refString="Van de Vijver B. &amp; Beyens L. 1996. Freshwater diatom communities of the Stromness Bay area, South Georgia. Antarctic Science 8 (4): 359 - 368. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0954102096000533" type="journal article" year="1996">Van de Vijver &amp; Beyens 1996</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Van de Vijver B. &amp; Ledeganck P. &amp; Beyens L." box="[662,969,1057,1084]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="28 - 36" refId="ref10149" refString="Van de Vijver B., Ledeganck P. &amp; Beyens L. 2001. Habitat preferences in freshwater diatom communities from sub-Antarctic Iles Kerguelen. Antarctic Science 13: 28 - 36. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0954102001000050" type="journal article" year="2001">
Van de Vijver 
<emphasis box="[837,898,1057,1083]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">et al.</emphasis>
2001
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Van de Vijver B. &amp; Frenot Y. &amp; Beyens L." box="[984,1046,1057,1083]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="1 - 412" refId="ref10196" refString="Van de Vijver B., Frenot Y. &amp; Beyens L. 2002. Freshwater diatoms from Ile de la Possession (Crozet archipelago, Subantarctica). Bibliotheca Diatomologica 46: 1 - 412." type="journal article" year="2002">2002</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Van de Vijver B. &amp; Beyens L. &amp; Vincke S. &amp; Gremmen N." box="[1059,1121,1057,1083]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="532 - 543" refId="ref10233" refString="Van de Vijver B., Beyens L., Vincke S. &amp; Gremmen N. 2004. Moss-inhabiting diatom communities from Heard Island, sub-Antarctic. Polar Biology 27: 532 - 543. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00300 - 004 - 0629 - x" type="journal article" year="2004">2004</bibRefCitation>
, 2008). In many cases, very large populations could be observed, occasionally up to 60–80% of all counted valves. These data indicate that this is typical limno-terrestrial taxon preferring wet moss vegetations in pools, bogponds and lakes with a pH between 5.2 and 7.4 and a low conductivity (&lt;160 µS/cm). These data confirm the final conclusion in 
<bibRefCitation author="Witkowski A. &amp; Kulikovskiy M. &amp; Riaux-Gobin C." box="[460,743,1200,1226]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="61 - 68" refId="ref10775" refString="Witkowski A., Kulikovskiy M. &amp; Riaux-Gobin C. 2012. Achnanthidium sieminskae, a new diatom species from the Kerguelen Archipelago (Austral Islands). In: Wolowski K., Kaczmarska I., Ehreman J. M. &amp; Wojtal A. Z. (eds) Current advances in algal taxonomy and its applications: phylogenetic, ecological and applied perspective: 61 - 68. Polish Academy of Sciences, Krakow." type="book chapter" year="2012">
Witkowski 
<emphasis box="[596,656,1200,1226]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">et al.</emphasis>
(2012)
</bibRefCitation>
that the observed valves in their study are the result of the redeposition of a freshwater species in a marine environment. Given the large amount of available data and material, it is a pity the original authors did not verify their rather unusual observation more carefully.
</paragraph>
